     1	# SQLAlchemy 2 Cutover
     2	
     3	This cutover removes the legacy helper-owned commits that caused the
     4	2026-04-07 rollback. The SQLAlchemy 2 migration is only considered ready when
     5	repository reads use `select(...)` and each caller owns a single explicit
     6	transaction boundary for its full unit of work.
     7	
     8	## Behavioral changes
     9	
    10	- Repository helpers no longer call `commit()`. They add, flush, and read
    11	  rows inside the caller's transaction.
    12	- Worker settlement runs in one explicit transaction per call. A forced failure
    13	  after marking `processing` must roll back to `pending` so retries start clean.
    14	- Admin planning and reconciliation own their transaction boundaries as well.
    15	  Dry-run paths must roll back instead of queueing real work.
    16	
    17	## Recovery checks before release
    18	
    19	- Force `settle_entry(..., fail_after_mark=True)` and verify the row is still
    20	  `pending`.
    21	- Force admin dry-run planning and verify no row remains `queued`.
    22	- Force a batch failure and verify the entire batch rolls back instead of
    23	  persisting partial retry state.
    24	
    25	## Rollback steps
    26	
    27	1. Stop new worker and admin runs.
    28	2. Revert the application deploy to the previous release.
    29	3. Inspect `ledger_entries` for rows left in `processing` or `queued` from the
    30	   failed attempt.
    31	4. Reset those rows to `pending` before re-enabling retries.
    32	5. Re-run the recovery checks above before attempting the cutover again.

